"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"about 1375","1319":"1319","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Great Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Great Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Hatfield (East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, Nottinghamshire, Worcestershire, Herefordshire, Hertfordshire, Essex), or Heathfield (Sussex, Somerset), though not all of these have given rise to hereditary surnames. The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":33,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Hatfield was born in 1349, in Hatfield, Yorkshire, England, his father, Stephen de Hatfield, was 30 and his mother, Agnes Seton, was 30. He married Margaret Staunton about 1375, in Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1402, in his hometown, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1349–1402":"1349–1402","1349–1381":"1349–1381","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1379–1412":"1379–1412","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1319–1360":"1319–1360","1319–1351":"1319–1351","from 1375 to 1381":"1375 kuni 1381","ABT 1345":"umbes 1345","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","from 1376 to 1381":"1376 kuni 1381","1390":"1390","1349":"1349","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1412":"1412","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"umbes 1375","1319":"1319","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Great Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Great Hatfield, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1349–1402":"1349–1402","1349–1381":"1349–1381","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1379–1412":"1379–1412","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1319–1360":"1319–1360","1319–1351":"1319–1351","from 1375 to 1381":"vuodesta 1375 vuoteen 1381","ABT 1345":"noin 1345","1351":"1351","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","from 1376 to 1381":"vuodesta 1376 vuoteen 1381","1390":"1390","1349":"1349","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","1412":"1412","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"noin 1375","1319":"1319","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, En